[If one compares the case numbers and deaths from measles to Ebola in the DRC this year [2019], measles dwarfs Ebola; yet the support and funding for Ebola dwarfs measles. This is most likely because Ebola is much more in the international public eye. Between January and early August 2019, over 145 000 people have been infected with measles, and 2758 have died in the DRC as compared with Ebola, 2861 cases, with 1921 deaths. This is in spite of the number of children between 6 months and 5 years old who have been vaccinated with MMR vaccine, 474 860, compared with approximately 160 000 individuals vaccinated against Ebola.

USD 2.5 million has been raised out of the USD 8.9 million required to control measles, compared with hundreds of millions of dollars to fight Ebola.

To address the problem of maintenance of a cold chain during transportation to remote areas, vaccines could be delivered by drones and integrated into the existing health system. This has been done to bring vaccines to the "hard-to-reach Congolese village, Widjifake." Read: https://www.villagereach.org/press-release-drone-fleet-transports-vaccines-to-immunize-children-in-remote-health-facilities-in-drc/; Press Release: Drone Fleet Transports Vaccines to Immunize Children in Remote Health Facilities in DRC. - Mod.LK]

